Why R?

  • Its free. You can download and install from its web site
  • Online support and help
    • a collaborative effort
    • many volunteers are dedicating their times for new users
  • It is a complete statistical software which allows data manipulation and visualization
  • It can produce powerful and elegant data graphics

For more information review this lecture

ggplot

  • An R package to generate static data plot
    • very high quality graphics
    • standards and grammar of graphics are set by default
    • to install the package run this one time in R console
  install.packages("ggplot2")
  library(ggplot2)
  • The package is written by Hadley Wickham
    • many people contributed in making it what it is now

Tips data: a case study

  • Cook et. al.: Interactive and Dynamic Graphics for Data Analysis
  • Does the tip rate depend on the size?
tips <- read.csv("http://www.ggobi.org/book/data/tips.csv")
tips$rate <- with(tips,tip/totbill)
model <- lm(rate~size, data=tips)
summary(model)$coefficients

                Estimate  Std. Error   t value     Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept)  0.184375028 0.011191325 16.474817 2.093730e-41
size        -0.009173328 0.004085378 -2.245405 2.564555e-02
  • When the party size increases by 1 person, tip rate decreases by about 1%

    tip rate = 0.18 - 0.01 * size

Tips data: explore the tips

  • Let us explore the distribution of tips
library(ggplot2) 
ggplot(tips) +
  geom_histogram(aes(tip), binwidth=1) + 
  scale_x_continuous(
    breaks=seq(2,10,by=2))

  • Now change the binwidth to .1
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(tips) + geom_histogram(aes(tip), binwidth=0.1)+ 
  scale_x_continuous(
    breaks=seq(2,10,by=2))

Tips data: explore the relationship

  • Adding layer
ggplot(tips,
       aes(totbill,tip)) +
  geom_point()


ggplot(tips,
       aes(totbill,tip)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se=F)

Tips data: include more variables

ggplot(tips,
       aes(totbill,tip)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se=F) +
  facet_grid(sex~smoker)

Creating a plot piece by piece

p <- ggplot(data=tips, aes(x=totbill,y=tip)) 
p + geom_point(size=3) + geom_smooth(method="lm", se=F)

Creating a plot piece by piece

p <- ggplot(data=tips, aes(x=totbill,y=tip,color=sex)) 
p + geom_point(size=3) + geom_smooth(method="lm", se=F)

Creating a plot piece by piece

p + geom_point(size=3) + geom_smooth(method="lm",se=F) + facet_wrap(~time)

Some useful functions

  • Geometric functions:
    geom_point() geom_line() geom_bar() geom_histogram() geom_density() geom_boxplot()

  • Statistics:
    stat_smooth() stat_quantile()

  • Faceting:
    facet_wrap() facet_grid()

  • Scaling:
    scale_x_continuous() scale_y_continuous() scale_y_log10()

  • Theme:
    theme_bw() theme_gray()

  • For more please visit http://docs.ggplot2.org/current/index.html

Example: multilayer and theme

ggplot(tips, aes(totbill)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..)) +
  geom_density(size=1.5, color="steelblue") +
  theme_bw(18)

Example: legend and labels

ggplot(tips, aes(factor(size),tip,color=factor(size))) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=factor(size)), alpha=0.3) +
  xlab("Party size") +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Changing scales

Source: tidyr by Hadley Wickham

codes for Changing scales

n <- runif(100,min=1,max=100)
y <- exp(0.5-log(n)+rnorm(100,0,.1))
dat <- data.frame(n,y)
ggplot(dat, aes(n,y)) + 
  geom_point()


ggplot(dat, aes(n,y)) + 
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10() + 
  scale_y_log10()
